---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Candidates" currentPath="/candidates">
  <div class="hero-stripe">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>The Candidates</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Background on the two major candidates in the 2026 Democratic primary.</p>
      <p class="meta">Primary: September 9, 2026 · Early voting begins August 20</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container" style="padding-bottom: 80px;">

    <div class="compare-grid" style="margin-top: 0;">

      <div class="compare-col col-smiley">
        <div style="margin-bottom: 6px;"><span class="candidate-tag smiley">Incumbent</span></div>
        <div class="compare-col-header">Brett Smiley</div>
        <div class="compare-col-role">Mayor of Providence, 2022–present · Age 46</div>
        <a href="https://www.smileyformayor.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="display:inline-block;font-size:0.72rem;letter-spacing:0.06em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--pvd-red);border-bottom:1px solid var(--pvd-red);padding-bottom:1px;margin-bottom:20px;">smileyformayor.com →</a>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Background</div>
          <p>Grew up outside Chicago. DePaul University (finance, MBA). Campaign manager for congressional races in Illinois before moving to Rhode Island. Served under Mayors Cicilline and Elorza, then as Chief of Staff and Director of Administration under Governor Raimondo. First openly gay mayor of Providence. Won 2022 Democratic primary with 42%.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Core Platform</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Fiscal discipline and deficit reduction</li>
            <li>Supply-side housing: build more units at all price points</li>
            <li>Public safety investment — crime at 30-year low</li>
            <li>School construction: every student in new/renovated building by 2030</li>
            <li>Opposition to federal overreach under Trump administration</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Key Accomplishments Claimed</div>
          <ul>
            <li>$223M PILOT agreement with colleges & universities — doubled prior contributions</li>
            <li>1,600+ housing units built or preserved</li>
            <li>Violent crime at 30-year low</li>
            <li>Universal pre-K expansion</li>
            <li>Real Time Crime Center launched</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Key Vulnerabilities</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Vetoed the City Council's rent stabilization ordinance — opposed a position with 74% voter support</li>
            <li>On the wrong side of the most salient issue in the race</li>
            <li>Built a summer house in Tiverton while affordability crisis worsened</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Campaign Finance</div>
          <p>$1.3M cash on hand (end of 2025) · $250K+ raised Q1 2026 · 14x Morales's starting cash position</p>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Path to Victory</div>
          <p>Win the East Side and South Side. Hold homeowners in Mount Pleasant and Elmhurst. No incumbent mayor has lost a primary in Providence since 1974.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="compare-col col-morales">
        <div style="margin-bottom: 6px;"><span class="candidate-tag morales">Challenger</span></div>
        <div class="compare-col-header">David Morales</div>
        <div class="compare-col-role">RI State Representative, District 7 · Age 27</div>
        <a href="https://www.davidmoralespvd.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="display:inline-block;font-size:0.72rem;letter-spacing:0.06em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--pvd-red);border-bottom:1px solid var(--pvd-red);padding-bottom:1px;margin-bottom:20px;">davidmoralespvd.com →</a>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Background</div>
          <p>Born in Soledad, California. Raised by a single mother and Mexican immigrant. BA Urban Studies, UC Irvine. Elected to RI House District 7 (Mt. Pleasant, Valley, Elmhurst) in 2020 — youngest Latino ever elected to a state legislature. Quit his legislative job in fall 2025 to run for mayor full-time. Identifies as a democratic socialist. Also a professional wrestler.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Core Platform</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Rent stabilization: cap annual increases at 4%</li>
            <li>Anti-austerity budget philosophy</li>
            <li>Environmental justice and green infrastructure</li>
            <li>Community benefits agreements for development</li>
            <li>Aggressive tenant and housing protections</li>
            <li>Vacancy tax on corporate real estate</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Key Accomplishments Claimed</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Banned rental application fees in Rhode Island</li>
            <li>Raised minimum wage pathway to $17/hr by 2027</li>
            <li>Expanded Medicaid to all children regardless of immigration status</li>
            <li>Capped monthly cost of insulin and specialty drugs</li>
            <li>Led opposition to Sea 3 fossil fuel expansion at Port of Providence</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Key Vulnerabilities</div>
          <ul>
            <li>No executive experience managing a municipal budget</li>
            <li>Central promise — rent stabilization — faces legal risk under RI home rule law</li>
            <li>Anti-austerity platform lacks specific tradeoff accounting</li>
            <li>Lower name recognition (46% of voters didn't know enough to rate him, per Data for Progress)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Campaign Finance</div>
          <p>$89K cash on hand (end of 2025) · ~$100K raised Q1 2026 · Rejects corporate PAC money</p>
        </div>

        <div class="compare-section">
          <div class="compare-section-label">Path to Victory</div>
          <p>Dominate the progressive West End and Smith Hill. Run close on the East Side (usually Smiley territory). Capitalize on Mamdani-wave momentum from NYC. Internal poll (Data for Progress, Mar 2026): Morales +11, 45–34, ±6 margin of error.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section-rule"><span>The Primary</span></div>
    <div class="prose" style="margin: 0; max-width: 720px;">
      <p>The Democratic primary on September 9, 2026 is the race that matters. Providence is a strongly Democratic city — the general election is a formality for the primary winner. Early voting begins August 20.</p>
      <p>Smiley formally launched his reelection campaign on April 27, 2026 with a show-of-force event at Roger Williams Park Casino. He enters with a 14x cash advantage and the historical protection of no incumbent losing a Providence primary since 1974. Morales has run a more visible street campaign to date, with 9,000 doors knocked and 20,000 phone calls made.</p>
      <p>The race is being closely watched as a potential echo of Zohran Mamdani's upset victory in the NYC mayoral primary — a young democratic socialist beating a better-funded establishment incumbent on a housing platform. Whether Providence's electorate, which is smaller and older than New York's, produces a similar result is the central question.</p>
    </div>

  </div>
</Layout>
